subsection.p:
dot product The dot product is defined, more generally, for any two m-dimensional vectors:
\vvec\cdot\wvec = \left[ \begin{array}{c} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ \vdots \\ v_m \\ \end{array} \right] \cdot \left[ \begin{array}{c} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ \vdots \\ w_m \\ \end{array} \right] = v_1w_1 + v_2w_2 + \ldots + v_mw_m\text{.}
The important thing to remember is that the dot product will produce a scalar. In other words, the two vectors are combined in such a way as to create a number, and, as we'll see, this number conveys useful geometric information.

statement.p:
 We compute the dot product between two
	four-dimensional vectors as

	  \left[
	  \begin{array}{c}
	  2 \\ 0 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\
	  \end{array}
	  \right]
	  \cdot 
	  \left[
	  \begin{array}{c}
	  -1 \\ 3 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\
	  \end{array}
	  \right]
	  = 2(-1) + 0(3) + (-3)(1) + 1(2) = -3\text{.}

assemblage.p:
 As with ordinary multiplication, the dot product enjoys some
      familiar algebraic properties, such as commutativity and
      distributivity.  More specifically, it doesn't matter in which order
      we compute the dot product of two vectors:

	\vvec\cdot\wvec = \wvec\cdot\vvec\text{.}

      If s is a scalar, we have

	(s\vvec)\cdot\wvec = s(\vvec\cdot\wvec)\text{.}

      We may also distribute the dot product across linear combinations:

	(c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2)\cdot\wvec = c_1\vvec_1\cdot\wvec +
	c_2\vvec_2\cdot\wvec\text{.}

subsection.p:
To see this, we will apply the Law of Cosines, which says that
\begin{aligned} \len{\wvec-\vvec}^2 \amp = \len{\vvec}^2 + \len{\wvec}^2 - 2\len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ (\wvec-\vvec)\cdot(\wvec-\vvec) \amp = \vvec\cdot\vvec + \wvec\cdot\wvec - 2\len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ \wvec\cdot\wvec + \vvec\cdot\vvec- 2\vvec\cdot\wvec \amp = \vvec\cdot\vvec + \wvec\cdot\wvec - 2\len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ -2\vvec\cdot\wvec \amp = -2\len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ \vvec\cdot\wvec \amp = \len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ \end{aligned}
The upshot of this reasoning is that
\vvec\cdot\wvec = \len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta\text{.}

assemblage.p:
The dot product gives us the following geometric information:
\begin{aligned} \vvec\cdot\vvec\amp = \len{\vvec}^2 \\ \vvec\cdot\wvec\amp = \len{\vvec}\len{\wvec}\cos\theta \\ \end{aligned}
where \theta is the angle between \vvec and \wvec.

